0.body: Welcome to AI Pocket References: Responsible AI. This compilation covers a broad range of Responsible AI topics including Bias and Fairness, Privacy and Security, Green AI, Responsible AI Product Development, and AI Safety considerations with modern AI techniques. These concise references are designed for AI practitioners, researchers, and decision-makers who need quick understanding and practical application of responsible AI concepts. Be sure to check out our other collections of AI Pocket References , including AI Fundamentals, NLP, and High-Performance AI Computing!

1.title: Energy & Carbon Footprint Tracking in AI

2.body: Carbon footprint refers to the total greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions caused by an activity. In machine learning, large-scale model training consumes significant energy, contributing to emissions.
2.breadcrumbs: Introduction ¬ª Carbon Footprint Tracking ¬ª Why Measure Carbon Footprint in AI?
2.title: Why Measure Carbon Footprint in AI?

3.body: AI‚Äôs Environmental Impact ‚Äì Large ML models require high computational power, leading to increased energy consumption. Optimization & Efficiency ‚Äì Identifying high-energy-consuming functions helps optimize and reduce resource waste. Regulatory & Compliance Needs ‚Äì Researchers, businesses, and policymakers aim to quantify AI‚Äôs carbon impact. Cost Reduction ‚Äì Efficient energy usage leads to lower operational costs. Measuring AI‚Äôs energy consumption allows better optimization, improved sustainability, and transparency in reporting emissions.
3.breadcrumbs: Introduction ¬ª Carbon Footprint Tracking ¬ª Why Track Energy & Emissions?
3.title: Why Track Energy & Emissions?

4.body: Measuring the carbon footprint of AI involves two main steps: Energy Consumption Measurement Tools like CodeCarbon use hardware sensors‚Äîsuch as Intel RAPL for CPUs and NVIDIA NVML for GPUs‚Äîto track power usage. We integrate power over time (kWh) to determine the total energy consumed during model training or inference. Carbon Emissions Calculation The total energy (in kWh) is multiplied by the regional carbon intensity (gCO‚ÇÇ/kWh) to estimate emissions using the formula: Total CO‚ÇÇ Emissions = Energy (kWh) √ó Carbon Intensity (gCO‚ÇÇ/kWh) Where: Energy = Sum of hardware power usage over runtime Carbon Intensity = Grid emission factor for the region For example, the Regional Carbon Intensity fetches location-based CO‚ÇÇ per kWh data from public sources (e.g., Ember Climate ). It can auto-detect cloud provider regions (AWS, Azure, GCP) or use user-provided location.
